 =20
  <div><p>Hi Terrell and all,</p><p>I've been busy with non-ham things =
most of today, but have now
      had time to read your five pdf docs. Your CI/CD pipeline is a
      *major* contribution to the WSJT project. I can't thank you enough
      for all the effort that went into it -- and for the clear way your
      documentation describes it for us. I can't wait to see it in
      action!</p><p>In no particular order, here are a few things that =
occurred to me
      as I read through your files.</p><p>&nbsp;- It should be fairly =
easy to add some execution tests to add to
      the pipeline, especially after the effort Steve has already put
      into a script that tests the decoders for each of our supported
      modes.</p><p>&nbsp;- We still use Qt5 so we can still support =
users with Windows 7.
      For the same reason, we probably want to maintain support for
      macOS 10.13 and later on x86 hardware. Can those builds be added
      to the pipeline?</p><p>&nbsp;- You made an excellent first cut at =
reasonable assignments of
      tasks and responsibilities. Group members should feel free to
      volunteer for other or additional tasks, and I will surely need to
      add Admin privileges to several others in our group.</p><p>&nbsp;- =
Your scheme does not mention a way of dealing with "release
      candidates." We have used "-rc#" releases to let brave users
      experiment with and test new ideas. Should we keep such a
      capability? Or maybe handle it differently, in =
future?</p><p>&nbsp;- About deploying your scheme for general use: I =
could grant
      full Admin privileges to Brian and Terrell, at least, and the two
